<font color="#FF0000">KALI TAL &amp; THE SIXTIES PROJECT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 29  5:14:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It was not my intent that my private email be posted to the POV list. Forwarding of private mail without permission of the author is unethical, and, arguably, illegal.  The reason I did not want the message forwarded was *not* because I didn't want to stand behind my words, but because I did not want to be drawn into exactly this sort of pointless and ill-advised discussion.<br><br>
I am politically progressive.  I am a feminist. I am an anti-racist.  I make no bones about that.  As such, I run a journal, a press, a conference, and a web site which are hospitable to my values.  If others don't like my politics or my attitude, I frankly don't give a damn.<br><br>
But the charge that I am &quot;anti-veteran&quot; is beyond laughable.  It is a common tactic for right-wing veterans to dismiss my work because it doesn't represent &quot;the veteran's viewpoint.&quot; Of course, by that they mean *their* view point.  Over sixty percent of the material published on the Sixties Project web site is written *by* Viet Nam veterans.  That includes hundreds of pages of veterans' works. I arguably publish more Viet Nam veterans than any literary publisher in the country.  Veterans are well-represented on the SIXTIES-L <br>
discussion list--far from being excluded, they often *are* the &quot;scholars, activists, librarians, students and researchers&quot; to whom I refer in my introduction to the list.  <br><br>
Knee-jerk assumptions that because a forum's perspective is antiwar it is also anti-vet reflect a profound ignorance of history--after all, Vietnam Veterans Against the War was the *largest* association of Viet Nam veterans until the late 1970s.  Those who attack the Sixties Project site also attack the veteran authors whose work it houses--authors who clearly disagree with the views expressed by many veterans on POV.  It is easier to bash a female non-veteran than it is to swallow the fact that not all veterans agree with your own right wing views, is it not?  And the far right is well known for taking the easy way out.<br><br>
An extremely abridged list of veteran authors I've published: Mark Adin, Paul Allen, Steve Anderson, John Baky, Steve Banko, Dan Barker, Victor Bausch, Robert Borden, Peter Brush, Kenneth Campbell, R.S. Carlson, Horace Coleman, David Connolly, Sean Connolly, Bill Crandell, Cortney Davis, Skip Delano, John Dofflemeyer, Tim Driscoll, W.D. Ehrhart, Rod Farmer, Alan Farrell, Helmuts Feifs, Jon Forrest Glade, Thomas Gribble, Harry Haines, Palmer Hall, Ed Henry, J.B. Hogan, Wayne Karlin, Timothy Kennedy, Norman Lanquist, Pete Lee, Gerald McCarthy, Frederick McGavran, Rod McQueary, George Mariscal, Timothy Martin, Richard Olson, Tom Page, Edward Palm, Leroy Quintana, Ron Ridenhour, Dale Ritterbusch, Larry Rottmann, David Sconyers, Dan Scripture, Bill Shields, Ernie Spencer, t. kilgore splake, Jeff Stein, David Vancil, Ron Wichers, David Willson, Ken Wolfe.  You can find their work at the Sixties Project web site:<br><br>
     http://jefferson.village.virginia.edu/sixties<br><br>
As I've said, I've no stomach for &quot;discussions&quot; such as these. I rarely read bad novels, I don't watch much television, and I don't frequent unmoderated lists or free-for-all Web sites.  I am posting this only because a large number of inaccurate statements about my work have been made in this forum, and I felt a need to set the record straight. 
<p><code>--   (Kali Tal) </code><p>


